Andy Warhol - Pioneer of Pop Art (People to Know)
Enslow Publishers | 2001 | ISBN: 0766015319 | English | 116 pages | PDF | 9.4 MB

"In the future everyone will be famous for fifteen minutes," said Andy Warhol, the artist who skyrocketed to fame with his paintings of the Campbell's soup can and of Marilyn Monroe. Warhol's pictures of everyday objects and his portraits of famous people helped define Pop Art. From sickly child to controversial artist, outlandish moviemaker to celebrity publisher, Warhol's personality and eccentric style made him an icon of an era. In a fascinating story rich with quirky anecdotes and quotes, Carin T Ford takes a candid look at the Pop Art movement of the 1960s and the many sides of the American legend known as the Prince of Pop
